Bergeron](https://jira.spring.io/secure/ViewProfile.jspa?name=tedberg)** opened **[DATAJPA-541](https://jira.spring.io/browse/DATAJPA-541?redirect=false)** and commented

ReadOnlyRepository can be created as an extension of Repository for an app, but this seems like basic functionality that should be included.  A sticking point mentioned in [DATAREST-299](https://jira.spring.io/browse/DATAREST-299) is that DomainClassConverter only works if your entity repository extends CrudRepository.

I am using DomainClassConverter against entities marked `@Immutable`, which are just reference data objects.  If ReadOnlyRepository were refactored out into a parent interface, it seems that DomainClassConverter should work against it instead of CrudRepository


---

**Affects:** 1.5.2 (Codd SR2)

**Issue Links:**
- [DATACMNS-102](https://jira.spring.io/browse/DATACMNS-102) Allow Repositories to be composed of an arbitrary number of implementation classes

'updated_at': '2022-04-20T16:16:17Z', 'closed_at': '2022-04-20T16:16:16Z', 'author_association': 'NONE', 'active_lock_reason': None, 'body': "**[Daniel Imber](https://jira.spring.io/secure/ViewProfile.jspa?name=imberda)** opened **[DATAJPA-972](https://jira.spring.io/browse/DATAJPA-972?redirect=false)** and commented

The query-by-example API is very useful and can (depending on the example) return a large number of results. It would be very useful if this facility allowed returning of a java.util.Stream to easy process results without a potentially large memory footprint.

Perhaps this is possible already buy I've not found this documents or via SO.

The idea would be to do something like:

Example example = ...
repository.findAllStream(example).forEach(...)


---

**Affects:** 1.10.3 (Hopper SR3)

So it's impossible for us to have:

```java
<S extends T> Iterable<S> findAll(Example<S> example);
<S extends T> Stream<S> findAll(Example<S> example);
```
...in the same interface. So I don't think we're going to do that.

You have two possibilities. One is to extend `CrudRepository` (or just `Repository`) and define your own:

```java
<S extends T> Stream<S> findAll(Example<S> example);
```

I actually tinkered with one of our test cases, implementing this:

```java
public interface UserWithOptionalFieldRepository extends CrudRepository<UserWithOptionalField, Long> {

	<S extends UserWithOptionalField> S saveAndFlush(S entity);

	<S extends UserWithOptionalField> Stream<S> findAll(Example<S> example);
}
```
And it worked just fine after I adjusted my test case consuming a `Stream` instead of a `List`. The alternative is to `.stream()` on your results.

Currently, IgnoreCase for In queries is ignored, for example:

```
findByFirstNameInIgnoreCase(Collection<String> names)
```

does standard query, without UPPER clause, and I think it should generate something like:

```
UPPER(entity0_.firstName) in ( UPPER(?), ... )
```

Bergeron](https://jira.spring.io/secure/ViewProfile.jspa?name=tedberg)** opened **[DATAJPA-541](https://jira.spring.io/browse/DATAJPA-541?redirect=false)** and commented

ReadOnlyRepository can be created as an extension of Repository for an app, but this seems like basic functionality that should be included.  A sticking point mentioned in [DATAREST-299](https://jira.spring.io/browse/DATAREST-299) is that DomainClassConverter only works if your entity repository extends CrudRepository.

I am using DomainClassConverter against entities marked `@Immutable`, which are just reference data objects.  If ReadOnlyRepository were refactored out into a parent interface, it seems that DomainClassConverter should work against it instead of CrudRepository


---

**Affects:** 1.5.2 (Codd SR2)

**Issue Links:**
- [DATACMNS-102](https://jira.spring.io/browse/DATACMNS-102) Allow Repositories to be composed of an arbitrary number of implementation classes

I created my own Repository interface 
public interface MyRepository<T, ID extends Serializable> extends JpaRepository<T, ID>, QueryDslPredicateExecutor<T> {...}
and the corresponding implementation
public interface MyRepository<T, ID extends Serializable> extends JpaRepository<T, ID>, QueryDslPredicateExecutor<T> {...}

Together with a FactoryBean and a Factory everything works fine. The only problem I had was that everything in QueryDslPredicateExecutor is private. So I had to copy a lot of code from this class into my implementation because I wanted to use the createQuery method. Is it possible to make QueryDslPredicateExecutor more subclass friendly or is this a bad idea?

Ralph

Turnquist'}, 'message': 'Switch back to unicode for the DOT substitute character.

MongoDB doesn't support "." in field names, so a Private Use Area character was used. This was originally stored in unicode format, but delomboking the code caused it to get transformed into another encoding. This causes issues on certain systems when building the software, so we are converting it back to its unicode representation. The character has been the same throughout, ensuring binary compatilibity.

See: https://www.compart.com/en/unicode/U+F607

Related: https://github.com/spring-projects/spring-session-data-mongodb/commit/d601e270fc4099e2167dd9b72f1054e6b293e76b#diff-57190a47726099e31fdf86b12b80206e2ae24feb28aacaf494b99557583df150L47
Closes #2053.', 'distinct': True, 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/spring-projects/spring-session/commits/7fc0ae47d5bc5eb60f6dd177f9166c633926640b'}]}

'comments': 1, 'created_at': '2022-04-16T07:21:19Z', 'updated_at': '2022-04-18T14:18:31Z', 'closed_at': None, 'author_association': 'NONE', 'active_lock_reason': None, 'body': 'My project is a Spring Boot project that uses Spring Data JPA + Hibernate. Recently, I found that the project startup time was getting longer. Later, I found through the log that during the project startup process, all the proxies that inherit the JpaRepository interface were created. Because there are many interfaces, the project takes up to 5 minutes to start. Most of the time is spent creating proxy classes. How do I solve this problem?', 'reactions': {'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/spring-projects/spring-data-jpa/issues/2489/reactions', 'total_count': 0, '+1': 0, '-1': 0, 'laugh': 0, 'hooray': 0, 'confused': 0, 'heart': 0, 'rocket': 0, 'eyes': 0}, 'timeline_url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/spring-projects/spring-data-jpa/issues/2489/timeline', 'performed_via_github_app': None}, 'comment': {'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/spring-projects/spring-data-jpa/issues/comments/1101444834', 'html_url': 'https://github.com/spring-projects/spring-data-jpa/issues/2489#issuecomment-1101444834', 'issue_url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/spring-projects/spring-data-jpa/issues/2489', 'id': 1101444834, 'node_id': 'IC_kwDOABBezc5Bprbi', 'user': {'login': 'gregturn', 'id': 311040, 'node_id': 'MDQ6VXNlcjMxMTA0MA==', 'avatar_url': 'https://avatars.githubusercontent.com/u/311040?v=4', 'gravatar_id': '', 'url': 'https://api.github.com/users/gregturn', 'html_url': 'https://github.com/gregturn', 'followers_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/gregturn/followers', 'following_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/gregturn/following{/other_user}', 'gists_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/gregturn/gists{/gist_id}', 'starred_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/gregturn/starred{/owner}{/repo}', 'subscriptions_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/gregturn/subscriptions', 'organizations_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/gregturn/orgs', 'repos_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/gregturn/repos', 'events_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/gregturn/events{/privacy}', 'received_events_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/gregturn/received_events', 'type': 'User', 'site_admin': False}, 'created_at': '2022-04-18T14:18:31Z', 'updated_at': '2022-04-18T14:18:31Z', 'author_association': 'MEMBER', 'body': 'Short of analyzing your specific domain model and all its repositories, one immediate option to test is switching to Boot's lazy initialization approach.

* Configure the whole app to use lazy initialization: https://docs.spring.io/spring-boot/docs/2.6.6/reference/htmlsingle/#features.spring-application.lazy-initialization
* You can also pick and choose by using the @Lazy annotation, whether its to set everything to lazy and disable it on a per-bean basis, or the other way around. (Can't remember if @Lazy annotation works when applied to a repository interface definition).

All that being said, lazy can simply speed up the time to when your app can start responding to requests. If those requests are attempting to invoke a bean that needs to talk to a repository, there may still be delayed reaction since things still need to "come up".

It's still possible this that this may require more benchmark analysis to see what's really happening. Are there cycles between your entities that are causing an expensive startup? Or something else?', 'reactions': {'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/spring-projects/spring-data-jpa/issues/comments/1101444834/reactions', 'total_count': 0, '+1': 0, '-1': 0, 'laugh': 0, 'hooray': 0, 'confused': 0, 'heart': 0, 'rocket': 0, 'eyes': 0}, 'performed_via_github_app': None}}

'closed_at': None, 'author_association': 'NONE', 'active_lock_reason': None, 'body': '**Describe the bug**
On Windows PC with Italian code page Windows 1252, building the project from source either by Gradle Wrapper o by Eclipse fails because of an illegal char constant. More precisely the constant is in MongoSession class and is named DOT_COVER_CHAR. A comment makes clear the intention to use a "very rarely used character". Unfortunately it appears that the encoding of the character gets messed on my machine and I end up having a char constant which is in fact the 3 chars long and this is illegal.

**To Reproduce**
Checkout the project on a Windows 1252 machine and run ./gradlew build.

**Expected behavior**
The project should compile successfully.

'closed_at': None, 'author_association': 'NONE', 'active_lock_reason': None, 'body': '**Describe the bug**
On Windows PC with Italian code page Windows 1252, building the project from source either by Gradle Wrapper o by Eclipse fails because of an illegal char constant. More precisely the constant is in MongoSession class and is named DOT_COVER_CHAR. A comment makes clear the intention to use a "very rarely used character". Unfortunately it appears that the encoding of the character gets messed on my machine and I end up having a char constant which is in fact the 3 chars long and this is illegal.

**To Reproduce**
Checkout the project on a Windows 1252 machine and run ./gradlew build.

**Expected behavior**
The project should compile successfully.

'2022-04-14T15:43:14Z', 'closed_at': None, 'author_association': 'NONE', 'active_lock_reason': None, 'body': '**Describe the bug**
On Windows PC with Italian code page Windows 1252, building the project from source either by Gradle Wrapper o by Eclipse fails because of an illegal char constant. More precisely the constant is in MongoSession class and is named DOT_COVER_CHAR. A comment makes clear the intention to use a "very rarely used character". Unfortunately it appears that the encoding of the character gets messed on my machine and I end up having a char constant which is in fact the 3 chars long and this is illegal.

**To Reproduce**
Checkout the project on a Windows 1252 machine and run ./gradlew build.

**Expected behavior**
The project should compile successfully.

'author_association': 'NONE', 'active_lock_reason': None, 'body': 'Repository method annotated `@Query`, nativeQuery is true and containing pageable parameter generate incorrectly count query for starting with whitespaces.

For example, above method derived counter query `select count(where) from user where user.age > :age `.
```
@Query("   \n"
+ "select * from user where user.age > :age"
+ "\n    ")
Page<User> findByGreaterThanAge(int age, Pageable pageable);
```
But, If query starting without whitespace, `select count(*) from user where user.age > :age `

I found that org.springframework.data.jpa.repository.query.QueryUtils.COUNT_MATCH regex not matched select query starting whitespace. when declaring a native query

```
@Query(value = 
"DECLARE @h geography;"+
"SET @h = geography::Point(45.27353320, -73.43387729, 4326); "
 , nativeQuery = true)
```

when executing the query here is what Hibernate is trying to execute:
`DECLARE @h geography;SET @h = geography:Point(45.27353320, -73.43387729, 4326);`

It remove a ":"

Is there any known workarounds in spring?
In the mean time I can probably use a STORE PROCEDURE, but would like to prevent that.

'2022-04-12T16:41:07Z', 'closed_at': None, 'author_association': 'NONE', 'active_lock_reason': None, 'body': "There appears to be no clean way to use a custom QueryDSL `JPQLTemplates` class when creating a query: `Querydsl#createQuery` is hardcoded to use either `EclipseLinkTemplates`, `HQLTemplates` or the default. It'd be great if the template could be customized there, or the method easily overridden.

**Use case**

We need to emit SQL that calls the unaccent Postgres function when using `StringExpression::startsWithIgnoreCase`. The customized template achieves that by overriding `Ops.STARTS_WITH_IC`. This is then usable in a custom repository implementation by injecting the `EntityManager` and creating a new JPAQuery: `new JPAQuery<>(entityManager, new SomeOverridenTemplate())` -- but when using `QuerydslJpaPredicateExecutor` the `JPAQuery` is generated within spring-data-jpa itself.
(If there's a cleaner alternative to do so, I'd be happy to hear :)", 'reactions': {'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/spring-projects/spring-data-jpa/issues/2362/reactions', 'total_count': 0, '+1': 'MEMBER', 'body': "In a nutshell, you would need the ability to swap out/replace `AbstractJPAQuery<?, ?> QuerydslJpaPredicateExecutor.doCreateQuery(QueryHints hints, @Nullable Predicate... predicate)` (which perhaps you've gleaned) since this is where Spring Data JPA calls Querydsl to fashion any/all queries based on predicates. This method, whatever it is, would also need access to the `EntityPath<T> path` to simply have the same information it currently uses.

As Mark said, hooking in your own `QuerydslJpaPredicateExecutor` indeed requires hooking into the machinery of Spring Data JPA's fragment registration process.

Based on your subsequent feedback, I'm not sure if there is any suitable alternative to registering a custom fragment. And if that is true, maybe we need a more user-friendly SPI to register custom fragments. That way you don't have to get into the guts of Spring Data JPA's machinery. I need to inspect the details to see how easy using either a market interface or an annotation would be.

```java
public class MyCustomQuerydslJpaExectutorFragment implements SpringDataFragment {}
```

or

```java
@SpringDataFragment
public class MyCustomQueryJpaExectutorFragment {}
```", 'reactions': {'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/spring-projects/spring-data-jpa/issues/comments/1096955063/reactions', 'total_count': 0, '+1': 0, '-1': 0, 'laugh': 0, 'hooray': 0, 'confused': 0, 'heart': 0, 'rocket': 0, 'eyes': 0}, 'performed_via_github_app': None}}

there are few issues open, that are related to JPQL queries not parsed correctly. 
* #1919
* #2348
* #2341
* #2074

* #2032

Since EclipseLink is already present in the project it does not bring in a new dependency. 
`JPQLParser` is located in `org.eclipse.persistence.internal.jpa.parsing.jpql`. 

Why use `JQPLParser` over the current approach? The current approach uses REGEX and String formatting magic that can be quite hard. A REGEX expression is quite limited and has less power than a full parser that utilizes the power of context free grammars. Using only REGEX is not a good idea since JPQL is not a regular language. Therefore JPQL cannot be represented only using REGEX. (see more [here](https://cs.stackexchange.com/questions/57225/why-descriptive-power-of-context-free-grammar-is-greater-than-regular-expression) and [here](https://stackoverflow.com/questions/559763/regular-vs-context-free-grammars) why REGEX is not powerful enough).', 'reactions': {'url': 'comments': 3, 'created_at': '2022-02-28T11:19:05Z', 'updated_at': '2022-03-28T21:42:18Z', 'closed_at': None, 'author_association': 'CONTRIBUTOR', 'active_lock_reason': None, 'body': 'I have seen that there are few issues open, that are related to JPQL queries not parsed correctly. 
* #1919
* #2348
* #2341
* #2074
* #2045
* #2032

Since EclipseLink is already present in the project it does not bring in a new dependency. 
`JPQLParser` is located in `org.eclipse.persistence.internal.jpa.parsing.jpql`. 

Why use `JQPLParser` over the current approach? The current approach uses REGEX and String formatting magic that can be quite hard. A REGEX expression is quite limited and has less power than a full parser that utilizes the power of context free grammars. Using only REGEX is not a good idea since JPQL is not a regular language. Therefore JPQL cannot be represented only using REGEX. (see more [here](https://cs.stackexchange.com/questions/57225/why-descriptive-power-of-context-free-grammar-is-greater-than-regular-expression) and [here](https://stackoverflow.com/questions/559763/regular-vs-context-free-grammars) why REGEX is not powerful enough).', 'reactions': {'url': 'comments': 3, 'created_at': '2021-09-30T10:08:20Z', 'updated_at': '2022-03-28T21:37:33Z', 'closed_at': None, 'author_association': 'NONE', 'active_lock_reason': None, 'body': 'As per the comments on this closed [issue](https://github.com/spring-projects/spring-data-jpa/issues/1404), I'm opening a new issue, because sorting still doesn't work for aliases in all cases.

The regex patterns in `org.springframework.data.jpa.repository.query.QueryUtils` are not broad enough.

> The FUNCTION_PATTERN in QueryUtils looks like this:
>
>```
>builder = new StringBuilder();
>// any function call including parameters within the brackets
>builder.append("\\w+\\s*\\([\\w\\.,\\s'=]+\\)");
>// the potential alias
>builder.append("\\s+[as|AS]+\\s+(([\\w\\.]+))");
>FUNCTION_PATTERN = compile(builder.toString());
>```
>which only considers a single pair of parenthesis, but not two or more. So, for example, the earlierstBundleStart is not detected in this query:
>
> 
>
>```
>SELECT DISTINCT(event.id) as id,
>event.name as name,
>event.top_event as topEvent,
>event.ranking as ranking,
>MIN(bundle.base_price_amount) as cheapestBundlePrice,
>MIN(DATE(bundle.start)) as earliestBundleStart,
>..
>```


There was also a question on SO about this [here](https://stackoverflow.com/q/43993952/401712), where many people state that they are facing the same issue.

There are and have been several issues (at least https://github.com/spring-projects/spring-data-jpa/issues/1404, https://github.com/spring-projects/spring-data-jpa/issues/1724, https://github.com/spring-projects/spring-data-jpa/issues/1919) with the regex patterns in QueryUtils. I'm wondering, isn't there any more reliable way to parse the queries than with a regex (possibly an AST that is used also to execute the query)?

I am trying to run this native query with spring-data on version `2.5.0`

`@Query(value = "SELECT dense_rank() OVER (ORDER BY rank DESC)," +
        "t.id, " +
        "FROM table t WHERE t.x > 0 ",
        nativeQuery = true)

But I am getting SQLGrammarException because the spring-data engine will translate this query into

`SELECT dense_rank() OVER (ORDER BY rank DESC),t.id FROM table t WHERE t.x > 0 , t.y desc limit 20`

Where the problem is pretty obvious. There is ORDER BY clause missing, probably because of presence of ORDER BY clause in OVER subquery. Is this a known bug? '2021-10-19T08:34:26Z', 'updated_at': '2022-03-28T17:25:45Z', 'closed_at': '2022-03-28T17:25:45Z', 'author_association': 'NONE', 'active_lock_reason': None, 'body': 'It seems that there is newline character after the entity alias name in `FROM` part of the query before the `JOIN` the distinct is removed from the count.

Incorrect behavior:
 
```java
@Query("""
    SELECT DISTINCT entity1
    FROM Entity1 entity1 
    LEFT JOIN Entity2 entity2 ON entity1.key = entity2.key""")
```

returns
 
```
select count(entity1) FROM Entity1 entity1
LEFT JOIN Entity2 entity2 ON entity1.key = entity2.key
``` 

Correct behaviour:
```java
@Query("""
    SELECT DISTINCT entity1
    FROM Entity1 entity1 LEFT JOIN Entity2 entity2 ON entity1.key = entity2.key""")
```

returns
 
```
select count(DISTINCT entity1) FROM Entity1 entity1 LEFT JOIN Entity2 entity2 ON entity1.key = entity2.key
``` 

From testing if the `FROM` and `JOIN` are in the same line, and `WHERE` is new line then this incorrect behavior  also occurs.

For now I have solved it with `countProjection = "distinct entity1"`.', 'reactions': {'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/spring-projects/spring-data-jpa/issues/2341/reactions', 'total_count': 0, '+1': 0, '-1': 0, 'laugh': 0, 'hooray': 0, 'confused': 0, 'heart': 0, 'rocket': 0, 'eyes': 0}, 'timeline_url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/spring-projects/spring-data-jpa/issues/2341/timeline', 'performed_via_github_app': None}}
